In the near-field of the TERS tip, the intensity of Raman signal from the analyte molecules is proportional to the fourth power of the local electric field. Hence, for near-field and far-field electric-field intensity ENF and EFF, respectively, the enhancement of Raman signal (ρ) is equal to [22, 28]1ρ=ENFEFF4\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ \rho ={\left(\frac{E_{NF}}{E_{FF}}\right)}^4 $$\end{document}

The Raman enhancement factor (EF) in a TERS experiment is calculated using [29]2EF=ITip−inITip−out−1AFFANF\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ EF=\left(\frac{I_{Tip- in}}{I_{Tip- out}}-1\right)\frac{A_{FF}}{A_{NF}} $$\end{document}

where ITip − in and ITip − out are the Raman peak intensities measured with the tip in contact and retracted from the sample; AFF is the area of the far-field laser probe; ANF is the effective area of TERS probe, which is usually estimated from the geometric diameter of the tip-apex. The term ITip−inITip−out−1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
